The Telegraph - Calcutta : Nation

 Left swaps notes on terror

 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT

 New Delhi, Jan. 1: A Bangladesh Communist Party (BCP) team has told Left leaders that growing fundamentalist and terrorist activities has turned the situation explosive in their country.

 Party general secretary Mujahidul Islam Salim met the CPMs Prakash Karat yesterday and CPI leader A.B. Bardhan today. We compared notes on the situation in the two countries, Salim said.

 The Bangladeshi leader has sought a meeting with defence minister Pranab Mukherjee also to let him know about the highly dangerous situation. 

 There are as many as 58 fundamentalist terrorist outfits and over 100 training camps in Bangladesh. There is cross-border movement. The ISI has a strong network.

 Terrorist activities in Bangladesh have peaked in the past few months. Bengal and the UPA have voiced concern about Bangladesh training terrorists who operate in India.

 When Karat told Salim about this, he agreed ? a change from Dhakas stand, which has denied the allegation every time Delhi raised it.




